<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f101173547020494>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=>All about the Chanter...</a> <a id=fs8 href=#post><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." width="17" height="11"></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Jan 22nd 5:38 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=/db/poster.html?user=83141><span id=Scholar>Ellon the Charming</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>37 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [2.85]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>&lt;insert Haste item here (FBSS)&gt; + Illusion: Werewolf (Str + Haste) + Boon of the Garou (more ATK) + Beserker Spirit (more Str + Damage Absorb) + Rune 3 (why waste Peridots?) + &lt;insert highest Haste spell here&gt; + Rod of Annhilation + Maxed out 1HB = Chanter rocking da hizzouse!!!<br><br>Sure, sounds like lots of spells, but it really isn't.&nbsp;&nbsp;A *decent* Enchanter would Haste himself BEFORE hasting his melees in order to time them, so you'd already have that.  I personally still use Rune 3 because I just need to be protected from 1 or 2 hits in order to control a mob, so that's that.  Illusion: Werewolf can be cast ahead of time.  All that's left is Beserker and Boon.  Boon is quick-casting, and Beserker doesn't take that long.  Besides, you're going to want to wait til your tank gets in good aggro before wading into melee.<br><br>With Clarity 2 up, you really shouldn't have mana problems.  Throw in the new Meditation buff, Intellectual Superiority, and medding for short periods will do you just fine.  So that takes care of the &quot;go med!&quot; problem.<br>Now, check it, a Chanter's best DD is like 1K damage.  If you can get 10 hits in with this bestial weapon, you've already done as much damage as one of your nukes.  With all the massive buffs, the hastes, and the skills, you should land 10 hits pretty easily (considering you aren't fighting some crappy mob, and are fighting something like Sarnaks in Chardok, or Drolvargs in KC, which take a little longer to kill).  The obvious counter-point is &quot;um, why not just nuke?&quot;.  The answer to that is two-fold:  A) You have barely no risk of getting aggro on yourself, and B) it actually is very mana-conservative, although at first glance, it doesn't seem to be.  Beserker Spirit and Boon are both cheap spells to cast (and are good for a couple of fights), and the rest you'll probably have on you anyway.  So instead of knocking off a full blue bub shooting off a nuke (if you have the open spell slot for it), you can just do some meleeing.  :D<br><br>BTW, I do have experience as a meleeing Enchanter, and although there are critics, an Enchanter can keep down a VERY mean stun lock.  The advantage to that is that you conserve your Cleric's mana on single pulls (unless you're an over-aggroing idiot), since a good stun lock will only take about half a blue bub of mana (if that).<br><br>Here are the spell lists I use, in case anyone wants to try it on their own:<br><br>*IF* I had a Rod of Annhilation:<br>1) Tashania<br>2) Dazzle<br>3) Color Shift<br>4) Color Flux<br>5) Reoccuring Amnesia<br>6) Buff slot (Clarity, GoM, Int. Sup., Brilliance, Insight, Haste, Rune 3, Illusion: Werewolf)<br>7) Beserker Spirit<br>8) Boon of the Garou<br>*In the 6th slot, I'd usually have Haste up, since that's the one with shortest duration.<br><br>Stun Lock Master (wielding Incandescent Wand)<br>1) Tashania<br>2) Dazzle<br>3) Color Skew<br>4) Color Shift<br>5) Color Flux<br>6) Reoccuring Amnesia<br>7) Buff slot<br>8) Boon of the Garou<br><br>*Since I don't need Str for the stun lock, I get rid of Beserker, and throw in Color Skew.  I always open with Color Flux, as it seems to resist least for me.  Color Skew has a slow casting time, so I hit that one last.  It's a real no-brainer:  Open with Color Flux, then Color Shift right after, then Color Skew.  Rinse and repeat.  By the time you're done casting Color Skew, Color Flux should be back up.<br><br>Anyway, I may have gone off-track somewhat, but my point was to not only say that this weapon would be deadly in the hands of Enchanter, but also to show how it could be done in an efficient manner.<br><br>BTW, my sig's wrong...I've dinged some.  :D</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>D'Tox</td></tr>
